explanation:
OS_ObjectIdGetById — direct callee of OS_lseek; its implementation may contain for-loops or call functions that do, and any loop in it contributes to the overall behaviour (MISRA requires inspecting called functions).

OS_GenericSeek_Impl — direct callee that is responsible for the actual seek logic; must be inspected for for-loops and for whether those loops use/modify objects that are visible to callers.

OS_ObjectIdRelease — direct callee; its body (and any loops inside it) must be examined because functions called from OS_lseek are part of the behaviour considered by the MISRA rule.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit — called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to inspect any loops or side effects that could interact with loop counters or objects modified in loop bodies.

OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex — called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; include because it may access/modify shared indices or objects used as loop counters or control flags.

OS_ObjectIdConvertToken — called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to determine whether it modifies token-related objects (possible loop control flags or counters) used in surrounding loops.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel — called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to check for loops or side effects that could violate the rule when invoked from within loop bodies.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish — called by OS_ObjectIdRelease; include for the same reason (loops/side effects in callees count toward loop-body behaviour).

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken — called by OS_GenericSeek_Impl; include because it may contain loops or modify objects that could be used as loop counters/flags in enclosing loops.

OS_object_token_t — the token type passed into OS_GenericSeek_Impl and used with ObjectId APIs; its structure/semantics are needed to determine whether functions modify fields that might serve as loop counters or flags (aliasing, modifications via functions matter for MISRA assessment).

OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, OS_SUCCESS — constants/macros used in the call to OS_ObjectIdGetById and the return-value check; include to understand semantics (e.g. whether passing the lock mode has side effects, whether success value maps to particular behaviour).
